3. Preliminary Results

A. Annual observations of juvenile hares

Fig. 1 shows total the total number of juvenile snowshoe hares trapped and observed each year across all sites.

As can be seen in this graph, number of juvenile trappings were not consistent from year to year. The greatest number trapped was 126 in 1999, the first year of the study. In 2002 and 2009, there were rhares_by_year_minjuvenile observations collected. The mean number of hares trapped by year wasr hares_by_year_mean`. While this appears to show a downward trend in juvenile hare population, the trend could also be a result of less offort put into data collection. Going forward, researchers should be be consistent about how many traps are set out and how often theyre checked to ensure accurate representations of snowshoe hare populations.

B. Weight comparison and descriptive statistics

Fig. 2 compares the mean weight (g) of male and female juvenile snowshoe hares across the three collection sites. NA indicates that the sex was unspecified.

Across all three sites, male juvenile snowshoe hares had a higher mean weight (g) than females and juvenile hares with unspecified sex. Both mean female and mean male weight was the highest at site bonbs. This seems to show that juvenile male snowshoe hares tend to be larger than females. There were no observations with unspecified sex at this location.

C. Juvenile hare weight difference analysis

Table 1 Descriptive statistics (mean, standard deviation, sample size) of weight (g) of male and female juvenile snowshoe hares.

Sex Mean Weight (g) Standard Deviation (g) Sample Size
Female 855 292 197
Male 946 333 163

According to the results, juvenile male snowshoe hares (mean weight = 946 +/- 333g) weigh 90g more (6.59%) than females (mean weight = 855 +/- 292g). This difference was determined to be significant (Welchs two sample t-test: t( 325.02) = 2.71, p = 0.007), and the effect size is small-moderate (cohens d = 0.29).

D. Relationship between juvenile weight and hind foot length

Fig. 3 examines the relationship between hind foot length (mm) and weight (g) in juvenile snowshoe hares, seeming to indicate a positive correlation between the two variables.

The relationship between hind feet length and weight appears relatively linear in juvenile snowshoe hares. A simple linear regression model revealed that hind feet length significantly predicts weight (R2= 0.3, p <0.001), with an average slope of 9.52. This means that for every millimeter increase in hind foot length, we expect an average weight increase of 9.52g. Furthermore, hind feet length and weight are positively correlated (Pearsons R = 0.55, p < 0.001). The resulting linear regression equation is as follows: \[ \operatorname{\widehat{weight}} = -279.34 + 9.52(\operatorname{hindft}) \]

The R2 value is small (0.3), so the linear regression model is only moderately adept at predicting weight from hind foot length. Additionally, based on the exploratory plots, the data appears to be heteroscedastic, with a greater variance in data as hind foot length increases. For this reason, I would not rely on a linear regression model along to represent the relationship between hind foot length and weight in juvenile snowshoe hares.

5. Summary

Our preliminary results reveal the following:

  • Total number of observations of snowshoe hares varies greatly year to year and appears to be declining. However, this could be explained by inconsistent data collection.

  • Juvenile male snowshoe hares tend to weigh more on average than females

  • There appears to be a moderate positive correlation between juvenile snowshoe hare hind foot length and weight

Next Steps:

  • Compare the relationship between hind foot length and weight in the entire population of snowshoe hares, to see if there is more evidence of a positive correlation

  • Apply multiple linear regression to model relationships between weight, sex, site, and age

  • Compare observation statistics with data collection behaviors to better understand juvenile hare population trends
